  "prompt": "Why are speedometers inaccurate?",
  "response": "Speedometers can be inaccurate for various reasons, including:\n\n1. **Mechanical Errors**: Traditional mechanical speedometers rely on a rotating cable connected to the transmission or wheel, which drives a magnet near a spinning disk. Any wear and tear or imperfections in these components can lead to inaccurate readings.\n\n2. **Calibration Issues**: Speedometers must be calibrated correctly to provide accurate readings. Factory calibration can vary between vehicles, and variations can occur due to manufacturing tolerances.\n\n3. **Tire Size**: The speedometer is typically calibrated based on the circumference of a specific tire size. Changing to tires with a different circumference (larger or smaller) will affect the speedometer's accuracy.\n\n4. **Temperature and Wear**: Environmental factors such as temperature can expand or contract mechanical parts slightly, affecting accuracy. Over time, wear and tear on mechanical parts can also lead to errors.\n\n5. **Electronic Speedometers**: Even electronic speedometers can display inaccuracies. They rely on data from sensors and electronic control units (ECUs). If these sensors malfunction or if there's interference, the speedometer reading can be affected.\n\n6. **Manufacturer\u2019s Intentional Over-Reading**: Some manufacturers intentionally set speedometers to read slightly higher than the actual speed to ensure compliance with legal speed limits.\n\n7. **Legal Regulations**: Regulations vary by country, and some may allow a certain percentage of inaccuracy in speedometers.\n\nWhile speedometer inaccuracies are generally minor, it's always good to periodically check it against a GPS-based speedometer for added verification.",
